        <section>
            <title>Comment: Finding the Probability of "At least one of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213348-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>..."</title>
            <body>
                <p>Recall that when we talked about the Complement Rule, we mentioned that we would
                    come back to it later and illustrate its strength. Well, the time has come
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213200-0500"?>to
                    do<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213159-0500" content="for"?>
                    that.</p>
                <p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213233-0500"?>Rule 3:
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>The Complement Rule<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213301-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213250-0500" content="(Rule 3:"?>
                    P(A) = 1 - P(not
                    A)<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213306-0500" content=")"?>,
                    together with the Multiplication Rule, is <em>extremely</em> useful for finding
                    the probability of events like "at least one of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213345-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>..." in several repetitions of a random experiment.</p>
                <p>For example,</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>10 people were randomly chosen. Find P(at least one of the 10 has blood type
                        O).</li>
                    <li>A student uses a random guess to answer 10 true/false questions
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213425-0500"?>o<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213424-0500" content="i"?>n
                        a test. Find P(the student gets at least one question right).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>The key here is to use the fact that the complement event is much easier to deal
                    with than the actual event of interest. Going back to our example:</p>
                <p>The complement to <em>"at least one of</em> the 10 has blood type O" is
                        <em>"none</em> of the 10
                    ha<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213614-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213613-0500" content="ve"?>
                    blood type O."</p>
                <p>The complement to "getting <em>at least one</em> question right" is "getting
                        <em>none</em> of the questions right."</p>
                <p>(Note how "at least one of" changes to "none" in the complement.)</p>
                <p>If you feel unsure about this, go back and redo the "Did I Get This" activity
                        <activity_link idref="_u4_m01_probability_rules2" target="self">on
                        <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213827-0500" content="this "?>page<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213831-0500"?>
                        2 of the Probability Rules section.<?oxy_insert_end?></activity_link>
                </p>
                <p><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214021-0500" content="Here is what we&apos;ll do next:"?></p>
                <p>We'll start with a very simple example
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213931-0500"?>in
                    which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213929-0500" content="where"?>
                    it is still manageable to find P(at least one of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213948-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>..<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T213938-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>)
                    directly, without using the complement rule. Then we'll alter the example
                    slightly and see how trying to find P(at least one of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214040-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>..<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214042-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>)
                    directly can get
                        <em><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214116-0500" comment="remove bold and all caps. use italics instead for emphasis"?>VERY
                        COMPLICATED<?oxy_comment_end?></em>, and how the complement rule comes to
                    the rescue. Finally, you'll check your understanding by attempting to solve a
                    similar problem yourself.</p>
            </body>
        </section>
        <example>

            <p>Two people are selected at random. What is the probability that at least one of them
                has blood type O? </p>
            <p>Here is our sample space S = { (O,O) (O, not O) (not O, O) (not O, not O) }</p>
            <p>The event "at least one
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214418-0500"?>person chosen
                <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214427-0500" content="of the two "?>has
                blood type O" consists of the first
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101130T153539-0500"?>three<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101130T153538-0500" content="3"?>
                possible
                outcomes<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214321-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                and
                therefore<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214326-0500"?>:<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
            <p>P(<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214434-0500"?>at
                <?oxy_insert_end?>least one
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214339-0500"?>person chosen
                has<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214334-0500" content="of them having"?>
                blood type O) = P((O and O) or (O and not O) or (not O and O)) = <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214517-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>.44<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214508-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214508-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.44<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214513-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                + <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214521-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>.44<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214523-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214524-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214525-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                + <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214527-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214529-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214530-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.44<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214531-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                = .6864.</p>
        </example>
        <p>Now we'll just alter the example slightly by randomly choosing 10 people instead of
            2<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214814-0500"?>:<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214813-0500" content="."?></p>
        <example>

            <p>A patient with blood type O desperately needs a blood transfusion. Since a person
                with blood type O can receive blood only from another person who has blood type O,
                the blood bank decides to choose 10 donors at random and hope that at least one of
                them has blood type O. Find P(at least one of the 10 donors has blood type O). To
                make things simpler, let's denote the event "at least one has blood type O" by L
                (for at <em>L</em>east).</p>
            <p>Solving this
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214851-0500"?>using<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214849-0500" content="by"?>
                the brute force method would require a prohibitive amount of work. As before, we
                would need to list all the possible outcomes of blood types of 10 people (using
                either "O" or "not
                O"<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214910-0500" content=" as before"?>),
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214922-0500"?>but<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214921-0500" content="only"?>
                this time there are
                1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T214926-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>024
                of them! We would then need to identify those outcomes that L consists of (i.e., the
                outcomes in which at least one of the 10 people has blood type O). Next, we would
                need to find the probability of each of those outcomes and add those probabilities
                up. <em>W<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215004-0500"?>hat a
                    pain<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215009-0500" content="HAT A PAIN"?>!
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215021-0500" content="HELP!"?></em><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215053-0500"?>
                There must be a better way.<?oxy_insert_end?>
            </p>
            <p>Instead of doing
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215131-0500"?>all the work
                listed
                above<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215129-0500" content="that"?>,
                we can use the Complement
                Rule<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215140-0500"?>,
                which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215143-0500" content=" that"?>
                says P(L) = 1 - P(not L). As we explained before, in this case "not L" is the event
                "none of the 10 have blood type O," or in other words that all 10 have a blood type
                other than O. So we can simply solve (using our regular notation from this
                module):</p>
            <p>P(L) = 1 - P(not L) = 1 - P(not O1 <em>and</em> not O2 <em>and</em> not O3
                    <em>and</em> not O4 <em>and</em> not O5 <em>and</em> not O6 <em>and</em> not O7
                    <em>and</em> not O8 <em>and</em> not O9 <em>and </em>not O10). Now, using the
                multiplication rule, = 1 - <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215257-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215258-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215258-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215300-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215301-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215302-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215303-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215304-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215304-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215305-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215306-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215307-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215308-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215309-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215310-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215311-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215311-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215312-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215313-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>.56<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215316-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                = 1 - .003 =
                .997<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215325-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
            <p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215327-0500"?>Therefore,
                <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215330-0500" content="I"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215330-0500"?>i<?oxy_insert_end?>t
                is almost certain
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215340-0500" content="then "?>that
                if we choose 10
                people<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215345-0500"?> at
                random,<?oxy_insert_end?> we'll find that at least one of them has blood type O.
                This result makes
                sense<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215401-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                since 44% have blood type O, and so out of 10 people it is almost certain
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215416-0500"?>that
                <?oxy_insert_end?>at least one will have blood type O.</p>
        </example>
