        <p>The purpose of th<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215446-0500"?>e<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215444-0500" content="is"?>
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215449-0500"?>following
            <?oxy_insert_end?>activity is to guide you through another problem that involves finding
            P(at least one of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215437-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>...<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215439-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>).</p>
        <section purpose="learnbydoing">
            <title>Learn By Doing</title>
            <body>
                <p>A quiz consists of 10
                    multiple<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215459-0500"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215459-0500" content=" "?>choice
                    questions, each with 4 possible answers, only one of which is correct. A student
                    who does not attend lectures on a regular basis has no
                    clue<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T215522-0500"?> what
                    the answers are<?oxy_insert_end?>, and therefore uses an independent random
                    guess to answer each of the 10 questions. What is the probability that the
                    student gets at least one question right?</p>
                <p>Let's decide on some notations.</p>
                <p>Let L be the event that the student gets at least one of the questions right.</p>
                <p>We'll use R for getting a question right and W for getting it wrong (W is
                    essentially "not R").</p>
